                  ASSOCIATION FOR COMPUTING MACHINERY
                     1994 COMPUTER SCIENCE CONFERENCE

             March 8-10, 1994 - Phoenix Civic Plaza, Phoenix, AZ.
                    Preconference tutorials on March 7, 1994.

                               Program Co-Chairs:
                          Laurie Werth and John Werth
                       University of Texas, Austin, Texas


CSC '94 - SCALING UP

Computer systems will once again undergo a remarkable surge in
capability in the next few years.  Advances in microprocessor
technology, the onset of widespread parallel computing, and
increases in network and bus bandwidths are fueling this surge.
However, these changes raise many questions:

        How can we design, develop, maintain, and warrant the quality
of the substantially larger  programs that will run on these
systems?

        How will computer scientists work with domain experts to create
new applications ?  What applications will evolve?  What new
human interfaces will be attainable?

        What new models of computing and computer use must we
develop  to use these new systems effectively?  What are the new
concepts, programming paradigms, and algorithms needed to
express the applications of the future?

        How must other components be scaled up to keep these
computer systems  in balance?  What software and algorithms are
required to compensate for unresolvable hardware imbalances?

As a community, we will address these issues:

        How we can forge industry/university /government
partnerships help shape plans the coming large scale national and
international  R&D projects that feature computing as their focus?

        How can we improve communication of evolving computer
science among our students, professionals in the field and society as
a whole?

We must both build on our previous work and escape the inertia
resulting from our previous successes.  With your help, we will
address these and other questions.

As the ACM annual conference, CSC '94 will also:

        Provide a forum for current research in computer science and
state-of-the-art practice using a mix of invited keynote speakers,
town meeting, tutorials, debates, panels, and papers.

        Introduce students to the broader computing community
through events such as a student poster session, employment
register, computer chess and programming contests, as well as
workshops and presentations on professional issues.

        Encourage ACM's leaders and conference participants to meet
and discuss Association initiatives that address the current and
future needs of the community.


CSC '94 INFORMATION FOR AUTHORS

Research papers, survey and tutorial articles, case studies, and
papers on novel implementations or applications are invited in all
areas of computer science for inclusion in CSC '94.  Authors should
submit five (5) copies of the complete paper (twenty double-spaced
pages using a 12-point font, about 6000 words).  Because the
identity of the authors will not be revealed to the referees, please
provide a separate cover page that includes the title, subject area,
all authors' names, and complete physical and electronic mail
addresses and telephone numbers.  The title should also appear on
the body of the paper.  In case of multiple authors please indicate
to whom correspondence should be directed  The Program
Committee may select outstanding papers to be considered for
publication in the Communications of the ACM.

Important dates:
August  6, 1993         Deadline for submissions
September 27, 1993      Notification of acceptance
November 12, 1993       Camera-ready version due

